  "commonName": "Wagtails & pipits",
  "children": [
    {
      "id": "GENUS_MOTACILLA",
      "name": "Motacilla",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Wagtails — slender, long-tailed passerines named for their incessant tail-pumping, which serves as a signal of alertness to potential predators. The white wagtail (sädesärla) is one of Sweden's most familiar and beloved birds, nesting on buildings, farms, jetties, and bridges across the country. It is among the first migratory birds to return in spring — its appearance is greeted as a sure sign that winter is ending. Wagtails walk with an elegant, deliberate gait, chasing insects on short sprints along the ground. They are strongly associated with human habitation in Sweden, and the sight and sound of a sädesärla bobbing on a roof is embedded in Swedish cultural memory.",
      "lineage": "Wagtails",
      "children": [
        {
          "id": "MOTACILLA_ALBA",
          "name": "Motacilla alba",
          "rank": "SPECIES",
          "commonName": "White wagtail",
          "lineage": "Wagtails",
          "continents": [
            "Europe",
            "Asia",
            "Africa"
          ],
          "subspeciesCount": 9,
          "description": "The white wagtail is a small passerine bird in the family Motacillidae, which also includes pipits and longclaws. The species breeds in the Palearctic zone in most of Europe and Asia and parts of North Africa; it also has a toehold in western Alaska as a scarce breeder. It is resident in the mildest parts of its range, but otherwise migrates to Africa.",
          "sourcedFrom": "wikipedia"
        },
        {
          "id": "MOTACILLA_FLAVA",
          "name": "Motacilla flava",
          "rank": "SPECIES",
          "commonName": "Western yellow wagtail",
          "lineage": "Wagtails",
          "continents": [
            "Europe",
            "Asia",
            "Africa"
          ],
          "subspeciesCount": 8,
          "description": "The western yellow wagtail is a small passerine bird in the wagtail family Motacillidae, which also includes the pipits and longclaws. This species breeds in much of temperate Europe and Asia. Most populations are migratory, moving south to tropical Africa and southern Asia for the winter; the small population breeding in Egypt is however resident there.",
          "sourcedFrom": "wikipedia"
        },
        {
          "id": "MOTACILLA_CINEREA",
          "name": "Motacilla cinerea",
          "rank": "SPECIES",
          "commonName": "Grey wagtail",
          "lineage": "Wagtails",
          "continents": [
            "Asia",
            "Africa"
          ],
          "subspeciesCount": 3,
          "description": "The grey wagtail is a member of the wagtail family, Motacillidae, measuring around 18–19 cm overall length. The species looks somewhat similar to the yellow wagtail but has the yellow on its underside restricted to the throat and vent. Breeding males have a black throat.",
          "sourcedFrom": "wikipedia"
